lor in the Long Eighteenth Century -- t14 The Crusoeiana: Material Crusoe -- t15 Adaptation in Strange Places: Terrence Malick’s To the Wonder and the Narrative Effect and Form of Samuel Richardson’s Pamela -- t16 Adapting the Tombeaux des Princes: A Study in Media Variations -- t17 Experiential Pedagogy to Join the Thread of Conversation with Paul et Virginie -- t18 “Lookin’ for a Mind at Work”: Hamilton, Adaptation, and Enlightenment Ideals for the Core Curriculum -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA collection of pedagogical essays that presents proven strategies for the teaching of adaptation and eighteenth-century textsThe eighteenth century was a golden age of adaptation: classical epics were adapted to contemporaneous mock-epics, life writing to novels, novels to plays, and unauthorized sequels abounded. In our own time, cultural products of the long eighteenth century continue to be widely adapted. Early novels such as Robinson Crusoe and Gulliver's Travels, the founding documents of the United States, Jane Austen's novels, Mary Shelley's Frankenstein-all of these have been adapted so often that they are ubiquitous cultural mythoi, even for people who have never read them. Eighteenth-century texts appear in consumer products, comics, cult mashups, fan fiction, films, network and streaming shows, novels, theater stagings, and web serials. Adapting the Eighteenth Century provides innovative, hands-on pedagogies for teaching eighteenth-century studies and adaptation across disciplines and levels. Among the works treated in or as adaptations are novels by Austen, Defoe, and Shelley, as well as the current worldwide musical sensation Hamilton. Essays offer tested models for the teaching of practices such as close reading, collaboration, public scholarship, and research; in addition, they provide a historical grounding for discussions of such issues as the foundations of democracy, critical race and gender studies, and notions of genre. The collection as a whole demonstrates the fruitfulness of teaching about adaptation in both period-specific and generalist courses across the curriculum.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturevAdaptations. 0aEnglish literaturexStudy and teachingy18th century. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 18th Century .2bisacsh  aAdaptation.  aAdapting.  aCultural Studies.  aEighteenth Century.  aGenres.  aHistorical Periods.  aLiterature.  aMasterpieces.  aPedagogies.  aTeaching Strategies.1 aBobroff, Maria Park, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrett, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBringardner, Chase, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoker, Cait, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoukopoulos, Lindsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Peggy Schaller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Emily C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGieger, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGulya, Jason J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGulya, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrow, Sharon R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrow, Sharon R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHultquist, Aleksondra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngrassia, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4